---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="IMWA Projection Table 7-C"
  description="Denominational Approval Severance Modeling: Asbury Theological Seminary and the Broader Protestant Sector. Prepared by the IMWA Denominational Severance Projection Unit."
>
  <article class="page">

    <div class="doc-header">
      <div class="doc-classification">FOR INSTITUTIONAL DISTRIBUTION · NOT FOR DENOMINATIONAL USE</div>
      <h1>IMWA Projection Table 7-C</h1>
      <div class="doc-subtitle">Denominational Approval Severance Modeling:<br />Asbury Theological Seminary and the Broader Protestant Sector</div>
      <div class="doc-meta">
        <span>Prepared by: Denominational Severance Projection Unit</span>
        <span>Institute for Ministry Watch Accountability</span>
        <span>Date: June 28, 2026</span>
        <span>Reference: DSPU-2026-7C</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Preamble</h2>
      <p>
        This table presents the findings of the IMWA Denominational Severance Projection Unit
        following eleven days of modeling in response to the United Methodist Church's removal
        of Asbury Theological Seminary from its list of approved institutions for ordination candidates.
        Two projection scenarios are presented: a conservative linear model (Scenario A) and the
        methodologically preferred exponential model incorporating the Ecclesiastical Friction Index
        coefficient of 0.73 (Scenario B). A sector-wide analysis follows as Table 7-C(ii).
      </p>
      <p class="model-note">
        <strong>Ecclesiastical Friction Index (EFI):</strong> A proprietary coefficient (0.73) derived from
        the IMWA's analysis of historical denominational severance events dating to 1517.
        The EFI represents the degree to which each severance event increases the probability
        and velocity of subsequent severance events within the same institution. An EFI of 0.73
        is described by our modeling team as "brisk."
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Table 7-C(i): Asbury Theological Seminary — Projected Approval Relationship Terminus</h2>
      <p class="table-note">Baseline: 14 approval relationships as of January 2024. Current: 13 (following UMC severance, 2025). Projection origin: June 2026.</p>

      <table class="data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Year</th>
            <th>Scenario A<br /><span class="th-sub">Linear (1/yr)</span></th>
            <th>Scenario B<br /><span class="th-sub">Exponential (EFI: 0.73)</span></th>
            <th>EFI-Adjusted<br /><span class="th-sub">Severance Rate</span></th>
            <th>Institutional<br /><span class="th-sub">Outlook</span></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="row-baseline">
            <td>2024</td>
            <td>14</td>
            <td>14</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Stable. Pre-event.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2025</td>
            <td>13</td>
            <td>13</td>
            <td>1.00 / yr</td>
            <td>Event horizon crossed.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2026</td>
            <td>12</td>
            <td>11</td>
            <td>1.73 / yr</td>
            <td>Watching continues.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2027</td>
            <td>11</td>
            <td>9</td>
            <td>2.99 / yr</td>
            <td>Concerned but functional.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2028</td>
            <td>10</td>
            <td>6</td>
            <td>5.18 / yr</td>
            <td>Concerned and tracking it.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2029</td>
            <td>9</td>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>8.96 / yr</td>
            <td>Taking it personally.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2030</td>
            <td>8</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>15.50 / yr</td>
            <td>Final relationship under review.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-terminus">
            <td>2031</td>
            <td>7</td>
            <td>0 ⁽¹⁾</td>
            <td>26.82 / yr</td>
            <td><strong>Terminal state achieved (Scenario B).</strong></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2035</td>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Scenario B not applicable.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-terminus">
            <td>2038</td>
            <td>0 ⁽²⁾</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td><strong>Terminal state achieved (Scenario A).</strong></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Table 7-C(ii): Sector-Wide Protestant Seminary Approval Relationship Projection</h2>
      <p class="table-note">
        Scope: All accredited Protestant seminaries maintaining at least one denominational approval relationship as of 2026.
        Theological Disagreement Coefficient: 0.73 (constant). Modeling assumes the Asbury event functions as a sector-wide triggering incident.
        The IMWA acknowledges this assumption is aggressive. The IMWA also notes that aggressive assumptions have historically proven correct.
      </p>

      <table class="data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Year</th>
            <th>Avg. Approvals<br /><span class="th-sub">Per Seminary</span></th>
            <th>Cumulative<br /><span class="th-sub">Severance Events</span></th>
            <th>Seminaries at<br /><span class="th-sub">Zero Approvals</span></th>
            <th>Sector<br /><span class="th-sub">Condition</span></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="row-baseline">
            <td>2026</td>
            <td>12.3</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>Nominal. One cloud on the horizon.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2035</td>
            <td>9.1</td>
            <td>847</td>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>Noticeable. Committee has been formed.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2050</td>
            <td>4.7</td>
            <td>3,291</td>
            <td>41</td>
            <td>Significant. Several committees.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2065</td>
            <td>1.2</td>
            <td>8,104</td>
            <td>189</td>
            <td>Critical. Committee on Committees convened.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2087</td>
            <td>0.3 ⁽³⁾</td>
            <td>14,440</td>
            <td>412</td>
            <td>Post-approval era. Historically unprecedented.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-terminus">
            <td>2091 (est.)</td>
            <td>0.0</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>All ⁽⁴⁾</td>
            <td><strong>Sector-wide terminal state. Modeling complete.</strong></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section class="footnotes">
      <h2>Footnotes</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Terminal state under Scenario B assumes EFI acceleration continues unabated. The IMWA acknowledges that
          intervening theological convergence, ecumenical goodwill, or the unexpected emergence of a unifying
          doctrinal framework could alter this trajectory. The IMWA assigns this a probability of 4%.
        </li>
        <li>
          Terminal state under Scenario A assumes the linear rate holds constant at one denominational severance per year.
          This is the conservative estimate. The IMWA does not recommend relying on conservative estimates.
          The IMWA includes them for the comfort of readers who prefer not to look directly at Scenario B.
        </li>
        <li>
          The 0.3 average represents a sector in which most seminaries have exhausted their approval relationships
          and a small number of outliers maintain a single remaining relationship, described by our analysts as
          "hanging on by a thin denominational thread." The IMWA is watching those threads.
        </li>
        <li>
          "All" refers to all institutions included in the 2026 baseline dataset. Institutions founded after 2026
          are not modeled here. The IMWA notes that any seminary founded after 2026, with full knowledge of this table,
          would be making a theologically informed but statistically inadvisable decision.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="signature-block">
      <p>
        Prepared and certified by the Denominational Severance Projection Unit,<br />
        Institute for Ministry Watch Accountability.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Rev. Thaddeus Overlook-Barnes</strong><br />
        Senior Fellow for Watching Studies<br />
        Chair, Committee on Projections<br />
        <em>Institute for Ministry Watch Accountability</em>
      </p>
      <p class="sig-disclaimer">
        The IMWA Projection Table 7-C is provided for informational and accountability purposes.
        It should not be construed as theological advice, denominational counsel, or a prediction
        of divine action. The IMWA does not predict divine action. The IMWA watches. These are different activities.
      </p>
      <p class="sig-back">
        ← <a href="/posts/013-modeling-the-cascade-if-one-seminary-loses-one-denomination-">Return to the full assessment</a>
      </p>
    </section>

  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page { max-width: 780px; }

  .doc-header {
    border: 2px solid var(--color-navy);
    padding: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    background: var(--color-bg-alt);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .doc-classification {
    font-size: 0.6rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-gold);
    background: var(--color-navy);
    padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem;
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 2rem);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .doc-subtitle {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .doc-meta {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.25rem 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-top: 0.75rem;
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
  }

  section { margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }

  h2 {
    font-size: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-navy);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  p { line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.95rem; }

  .model-note {
    background: var(--color-bg-alt);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-gold);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .table-note {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .data-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }

  .data-table th {
    background: var(--color-navy);
    color: white;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
    text-align: left;
    vertical-align: bottom;
  }

  .th-sub {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 400;
    opacity: 0.75;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.03em;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .data-table td {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem;
    vertical-align: top;
  }

  .data-table tr:nth-child(even) td { background: var(--color-bg-alt); }

  .row-baseline td {
    background: #f0f4f0 !important;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .row-terminus td {
    background: #fff3f3 !important;
    font-weight: 600;
    border-top: 2px solid #c0392b;
  }

  .footnotes ol {
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
  }

  .footnotes li { margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }

  .signature-block {
    border-top: 2px solid var(--color-navy);
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
  }

  .signature-block p { margin-bottom: 1rem; }

  .sig-disclaimer {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-top: 0.75rem;
  }

  .sig-back {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }

  .sig-back a {
    color: var(--color-navy);
  }
</style>
